 is what you want to do, it's probably better to separate the loading (`pd.read_csv`) from the data transformation. \r\n\r\n```python\r\nfrom sktime.forecasting.compose import RecursiveTimeSeriesRegressionForecaster\r\nfrom sktime.datasets import load_airline\r\nfrom sktime.regression.compose import TimeSeriesForestRegressor\r\n\r\nseries = load_airline()  # single pd.Series, could be replaced with a pd.read_csv() call\r\n\r\nregressor = TimeSeriesForestRegressor()  # time series regressor\r\n\r\n# this is the class to perform the reduction from forecasting to time series regression \r\nforecaster = RecursiveTimeSeriesRegressionForecaster(regressor=regressor, window_length=10)\r\n\r\nforecaster.fit(series)\r\nfcast = forecaster.predict(fh=1)  # single step-ahead forecast\r\n\r\n# if you want to see the transformed data set you can run \r\nX, y = forecaster._transform(series)  # currently hidden method\r\n```\r\n\r\n* we have a similar class (`RecursiveRegressionForecaster`) for using sklearn-like tabular regressors\r\n* making the `_transform` method public would be nice, but requires to do some more work on the transformer types and class hierarchy \r\n\r\nI'm happy to guide you through it if you're interested. ","reactions":{"url":"https://api.github.com/repos/sktime/sktime/issues/comments/646666770/reactions","total_count":0,"+1":0,"-1":0,"laugh":0,"hooray":0,"confused":0,"heart":0,"rocket":0,"eyes":0},"performed_via_github_app":null,"event":"commented","actor":{"login":"mloning","id":21020482,"node_id":"MDQ6VXNlcjIxMDIwNDgy","avatar_url":"https://avatars.githubusercontent.com/u/21020482?v=4","gravatar_id":"","url":"https://api.github.com/users/mloning","html_url":"https://github.com/mloning","followers_url":"https://api.github.com/users/mloning/followers","following_url":"https://api.github.com/users/mloning/following{/other_user}","gists_url":"https://api.github.com/users/mloning/gists{/gist_id}","starred_url":"https://api.github.com/users/mloning/starred{/owne